## 1. Fixed Income Liquidity

### 1.1 Importance of Liquidity in Fixed Income Markets

- **Definition of [Liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md)**
  - [Liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) in [fixed income markets](../../Financial%20Engineering/A%20Practical%20Guide%20to%20Bonds%20and%20Swaps.md) refers to the ease with which bonds can be bought or sold without significantly affecting their price.
  - It is a critical determinant of trading efficiency and [portfolio management](../../Financial%20Engineering/Fixed%20Income%20Derivatives/The%20Impact%20of%20Option%20Strategies%20in%20Financial%20%20Portfolios%20Performance.md).
- **Recent Developments in [Fixed Income](../Lecture%20Notes%20Bonds,%20%20Preferred%20Stock,%20%20and%20Structured%20Products.md) [Liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md)**
  - The structure of [fixed income markets](../../Financial%20Engineering/A%20Practical%20Guide%20to%20Bonds%20and%20Swaps.md) has evolved significantly,  with a growing shift toward electronic trading platforms.
  - [High-frequency trading](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/The%20High%20Frequency%20Arms%20Race.md) and algorithmic execution have become key drivers of this transition.
- **Drivers of [Liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) Growth**
  - *Reduction in Supply and Demand for [Liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md)*:
	- Market-maker activities have decreased due to regulatory and cost-saving measures,  reducing [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md).
	- Despite this,  demand for [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) remains high,  driven by asset managers and [institutional investors](../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Trading%20and%20Markets/Chapter%204%20Institutional%20Trading.md).
  - *Diverse Market Drivers*:
	- The increasing complexity of [financial markets](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions%20Lecture%20Notes.md),  driven by digitalization and big data,  has necessitated more efficient [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) solutions.
  - *Regime Shifts*:
	- Post-2008 [financial crisis](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%209-%20Bailouts%20and%20Bank%20Failures/Squam%20Lake%20Group%20Letter.md),  regulatory changes and central bank interventions have reshaped [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) dynamics.

### 1.2 Supply-Demand Relationship in Fixed Income Markets

- **Current Market Dynamics**
  - Market-makers have reduced inventories due to regulatory constraints,  leading to lower [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md).
  - Asset managers now dominate the demand for [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md),  creating an asymmetric [market structure](../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2010/Market%20Structure%20and%20Size.md).
- **Impact of Market Stress on [Liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md)**
  - [Liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) tends to evaporate during periods of financial stress,  as seen during the Fukushima nuclear disaster in 2011 and the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020.
  - Government bonds (e.g.,  U.S. Treasuries) remain highly liquid even during crises,  while [Corporate Bonds](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/II.%20The%20Roles%20of%20Banks%20and%20Derivative%20Markets%20in%20Resolving%20Problems%20Inherent%20in%20Debt%20Contracts/Class%202-%20Debt%20Contracts%20due%20to%20Lack%20of%20Information/Class%20Notes%202%20–%20Corporate%20Bond%20Contracts.md),  especially those rated below [investment](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) grade,  experience sharp declines in [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md).
- **Historical Context**
  - The low-interest-rate environment has fueled a surge in [corporate debt](../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2014/Corporate%20Bonds%20and%20Loans.md) issuance,  increasing the size of the primary bond market.
  - However,  trading volumes in the [secondary market](../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Engineering%20and%20Arbitrage%20in%20the%20Financial%20Markets/PART%20I%20RELATIVE%20VALUE%20BUILDING%20BLOCKS/Chapter%201%20-%20Purpose%20and%20Structure%20of%20Financial%20Markets/Primary%20Issuance%20and%20Secondary%20Resale%20Markets.md) have not kept pace with the growth in new issues.

### 1.3 Complexity of Market Drivers

- **Technological Innovations**
  - Digitalization and big data have enabled cost-effective order execution and data processing.
  - Automated trading systems and electronic platforms have streamlined [liquidity provision](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%206-%20Bank%20Runs/Bank%20Runs%20Deposit%20Insurance%20and%20Liquidity.md).
- **Regulatory Changes**
  - Post-2008 regulations have increased transparency and reduced risk-taking by market participants.
  - Market-makers now engage in transactions only when they can quickly match orders,  reducing their willingness to hold inventories during volatile periods.
- **Central Bank Interventions**
  - Central banks,  such as the Federal Reserve and the European Central Bank (ECB),  have stepped in as [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) providers through asset purchase programs.
  - These interventions have reshaped market structures,  influencing [Bid and Ask](Class%20Note%209%20[[Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information) Prices With Private Information|[bid-ask](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Bid-Ask%20Prices%20with%20Adverse%20SelectionPrivate%20Information.md) spreads]] and [portfolio](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) allocations.

### 1.4 Regime Shift in Fixed Income Markets

- **Pre-2008 vs. Post-2008 Market Dynamics**
  - Before the [Global Financial Crisis](../../Financial%20Engineering/8.%20Credit%20Modeling%20and%20Credit%20Derivatives.md) (GFC),  market-making was more robust,  with higher inventories and greater risk tolerance.
  - Post-GFC,  market-makers have reduced their activities,  relying more on electronic platforms and algorithms for [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) prediction.
- **Impact of Technology**
  - Technological advancements have reduced costs and improved order matching.
  - However,  during periods of financial stress,  market-makers still withdraw from providing [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md),  highlighting the limitations of these innovations.
- **New Market Environment**
  - The rise of electronic trading has increased market depth and narrowed [Bid and Ask](Class%20Note%209%20[[Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information) Prices With Private Information|[bid-ask](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Bid-Ask%20Prices%20with%20Adverse%20SelectionPrivate%20Information.md) spreads]] in liquid segments like government bonds.
  - Robo-advisors and electronic platforms now play a significant role in providing cost-effective trading solutions.

## 2. Trading Approaches in Fixed Income Markets

### 2.1 Types of Trading Approaches

#### 2.1.1 Request for Quote (RFQ)

- **Mechanics**
  - Bond managers request prices from multiple dealers for specific nominal sizes.
  - Execution occurs when a bid is hit or an ask is lifted.
- **Challenges**
  - [Currency](../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) management becomes complex when dealing with multi-[currency](../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) positions.
  - [Price quotes](../../Financial%20Engineering/Derivatives/Part%20III%20-%20Fixed%20Income%20Futures%20Contracts/Chapter%2011%20-%20Interest%20Rate%20Futures.md) may deviate significantly from [expectations](../Fixed%20Income%20Lecture%20Notes/FORWARD%20RATES%20AND%20TERM%20STRUCTURE.md),  leading to potential trade withdrawals.

#### 2.1.2 Order Placement

- **Mechanics**
  - Bond managers place orders against quotes provided by market-makers or [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) providers.
  - Execution depends on matching the order size with available [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md).
- **Key Features**
  - Prices are quoted but depend on the notional amount,  leading to significant price movements for large orders.
  - Systems like Bloomberg AIM provide transparency and reliability for order placement and execution.

#### 2.1.3 Auction-Driven Trading

- **Mechanics**
  - Primarily used for new issues or book-building processes.
  - Bond managers indicate interest by placing orders with size and spread limits.
- **Example**
  - A [portfolio](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) manager might place an order for a $500 million corporate bond issue with a spread limit of +125 basis points.
  - Allocation depends on the level of oversubscription,  with highly oversubscribed issues resulting in reduced allocations.

### 2.2 Mechanics of Bond and Foreign Exchange Trading

#### 2.2.1 Determinants of Bond Prices

- **Formula for Bond Prices**
  $$ P (t,      Q) = T (t,      S,      + OAS,      + l,      + e) $$
  - Where:
	- $$ S $$ = Local [currency](../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) interest rate curve.
	- $$ OAS $$ = Option-adjusted spread ([credit risk](../../Course%20Notes/Quantitative%20Trading%20Strategies%20Lecture%20Notes.md) measure).
	- $$ l $$ = [Liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) premium.
	- $$ e $$ = Residual factors.
- **Key Insights**
  - A widening OAS indicates higher [credit risk](../../Course%20Notes/Quantitative%20Trading%20Strategies%20Lecture%20Notes.md).
  - [Liquidity risk](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%207-%20CP,%20Repo,%20and%20the%20Crisis/Asset%20Backed%20Commercial%20Paper%20Understanding%20the%20Risks.md) and other factors can cause the observable price to deviate from the theoretical fair value.

#### 2.2.2 Calculating Notional Amounts

- **Formula for Notional Amount**
  $$ q_i = \frac{V_{PF} \cdot w_i}{P_i^{ASK}} $$
  - Where:
	- $$ V_{PF} $$ = [Portfolio](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) volume.
	- $$ w_i $$ = [Portfolio](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) weight of the bond.
	- $$ P_i^{ASK} $$ = Ask price of the bond.
- **Adjusting for Foreign Exchange**
  $$ q_i = \frac{V_{PF} \cdot w_i}{P_i^{ASK} \cdot FX_i^{fx-\text{BASIS}}} $$
  - Where:
	- $$ FX_i^{fx-\text{BASIS}} $$ = Foreign exchange rate for the bond’s [currency](../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md).

#### Example: Calculating Notional Amounts

::: {. Callout-note}

#### Example: U.S. Dollar Portfolio
- [Portfolio](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) volume: $400 million.
- Bond weight: 7.18%.
- Ask price: 102.83.

**Calculation:**$$ q_i = \frac{400,     000,     000 \cdot 0.0718}{102.83} = 27,     920,     000 $$

The notional amount to buy is $27.92 million.

:::

## 3. Challenges in Fixed Income Trading

### 3.1 [bid-ask spreads](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information.md) and Liquidity

- **Definition of [Bid-Ask Spread](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Bid%20Ask%20and%20Transaction%20Prices%20in%20a%20Specialist%20Market%20With%20Heterogeneously%20Informed%20Traders.md)**
  - The difference between the highest price a buyer is willing to pay (bid) and the lowest price a seller is willing to accept (ask).
- **Factors Affecting Spreads**
  - Market segment (e.g.,  government vs. [Corporate Bonds](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/II.%20The%20Roles%20of%20Banks%20and%20Derivative%20Markets%20in%20Resolving%20Problems%20Inherent%20in%20Debt%20Contracts/Class%202-%20Debt%20Contracts%20due%20to%20Lack%20of%20Information/Class%20Notes%202%20–%20Corporate%20Bond%20Contracts.md)).
  - Notional amount of the trade.
  - [Market volatility](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%209-%20Bailouts%20and%20Bank%20Failures/Class%20Slides%20On%20Terrausd%20Runs%202.md) and stress conditions.

### 3.2 Portfolio Allocation and Market Volatility

- **Impact of Price Movements**
  - Large swings in bond prices can alter [notional amounts](../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%202/Pricing%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md) and [portfolio](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) weights,  causing allocation drift.
  - Basket trades are used to mitigate this risk.
- **Example of Allocation Drift**
  - If a bond’s price increases significantly,  its weight in the [portfolio](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) may exceed the desired allocation,  requiring rebalancing.

## 4. Summary and Key Takeaways

- [Fixed income](../Lecture%20Notes%20Bonds,%20%20Preferred%20Stock,%20%20and%20Structured%20Products.md) [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) is a critical factor in bond trading and [portfolio management](../../Financial%20Engineering/Fixed%20Income%20Derivatives/The%20Impact%20of%20Option%20Strategies%20in%20Financial%20%20Portfolios%20Performance.md),  influenced by [market structure](../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%2010/Market%20Structure%20and%20Size.md),  technological advancements,  and regulatory changes.
- Trading approaches,  such as RFQ,  order placement,  and auction-driven methods,  offer flexibility but come with unique challenges,  especially in multi-[currency](../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) portfolios.
- Calculating [notional amounts](../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%202/Pricing%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md) and managing [Bid and Ask](Class%20Note%209%20[[Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information) Prices With Private Information|[bid-ask](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Bid-Ask%20Prices%20with%20Adverse%20SelectionPrivate%20Information.md) spreads]] are essential for maintaining desired [portfolio](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) allocations and minimizing transaction costs.
- Central bank interventions and technological innovations continue to reshape the [fixed income](../Lecture%20Notes%20Bonds,%20%20Preferred%20Stock,%20%20and%20Structured%20Products.md) market,  requiring bond managers to adapt their strategies dynamically.

This concludes the lecture notes on [fixed income](../Lecture%20Notes%20Bonds,%20%20Preferred%20Stock,%20%20and%20Structured%20Products.md) [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md),  trading approaches,  and [portfolio management](../../Financial%20Engineering/Fixed%20Income%20Derivatives/The%20Impact%20of%20Option%20Strategies%20in%20Financial%20%20Portfolios%20Performance.md). Next,  we will explore advanced techniques for optimizing bond portfolios and [managing interest rate risk](Lecture%20Notes%204-Mechanics%20of%20Futures%20Trading%20and%20Fixed%20Income%20Derivatives.md).

# Lecture Notes: Bond Trading Mechanics,  [bid-ask spreads](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information.md),  and Portfolio Management

## 1. Introduction to Bond Trading Mechanics

### 1.1 Overview of Bond Prices and Notional Amounts

- **Bond Prices and [Portfolio](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) Basis [Currency](../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md)**
  - Bond prices are universal and independent of the [portfolio](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md)'s basis [currency](../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md) (e.g.,  USD or EUR).
  - However,  the **[notional amounts](../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%202/Pricing%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md)** that a bond [portfolio](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) manager must order are adjusted by the foreign exchange (FX) ask price when denominated in a different [currency](../../Financial%20Instruments/Lecture%20Notes-%20Financial%20Instruments/Teaching%20Note%201-%20Forward%20Rates%20Agreement/Forwards%20and%20Futures%20Notes.md).
- **Impact of [Bid and Ask](Class%20Note%209%20[[Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information) Prices With Private Information|[bid-ask](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Bid-Ask%20Prices%20with%20Adverse%20SelectionPrivate%20Information.md) spreads]] on Rebalancing**
  - Rebalancing portfolios is directly influenced by [Bid and Ask](Class%20Note%209%20[[Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information) Prices With Private Information|[bid-ask](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Bid-Ask%20Prices%20with%20Adverse%20SelectionPrivate%20Information.md) spreads]],  which affect the [notional amounts](../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%202/Pricing%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md) required for trades.
  - Selling bonds is generally easier than buying because managers already know the [portfolio](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md)'s exposure and [notional amounts](../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%202/Pricing%20Interest%20Rate%20Swaps.md).
- **Minimum Tradable Increments**
  - Bonds often trade in specific increments (e.g.,  100,  1,  000,  or 100,  000).
  - For example,  a calculated notional amount of $27,     923,     344$ may need to be rounded to $27,     920,     000$ to meet tradable size requirements.

## 2. When and How Bond Managers Trade

### 2.1 Reasons for Trading

- **Common Triggers for Bond Trades**
  - Redemptions or inflows.
  - Allocation adjustments.
  - Regulatory requirements.
  - Urgent client [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) needs.
- **Timing of Trades**
  - The timing of trades is often driven by market conditions,  [idiosyncratic factors](../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%203/Spreads.md),  or immediate needs,  rather than strategic timing alone.

### 2.2 Trading Methods

#### 2.2.1 Discretionary Trading

- **Definition**
  - Discretionary trading involves single-security trades based on relative value analysis,  qualitative insights,  or quantitative tools.
- **Characteristics**
  - Irregular trading frequency,  often driven by news flows,  corporate events,  or changes in bond [fundamentals](../../Advanced%20Financial%20Analysis%20and%20Valuation/Lecture%20Notes%20Advanced%20Financial%20Analysis%20and%20Valuation/Week%202/Week%202%20Fundamentals%20Of%20Forecasting.md).
  - Decisions may involve geographic allocation,  sector preferences,  [foreign exchange exposure](../../Financial%20Engineering/Derivatives/Part%20VIII%20-%20Swaps/Chapter%2036%20-%20Currency%20Swaps.md),  and [duration](../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md) positioning.
- **Example: Discretionary Trade**
  - A bond manager decides to buy long-term Italian government bonds in euros due to a central bank's loose [Risk and Return](Lecture%207-[[Lecture%207-Risk%20and%20Return%20of%20Bonds) of Bonds#7.6 [Asset price](../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Asset%20Pricing%20Theory%20Overview/Chapter%204%20-%20State%20Prices/A%20Preview%20of%20Alternative%20Formulations.md) reactions to [monetary policy](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%209-%20Bailouts%20and%20Bank%20Failures/Articles/The%20Economist%20Regime%20Change.md) surprises|[monetary policy](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%209-%20Bailouts%20and%20Bank%20Failures/Articles/The%20Economist%20Regime%20Change.md)]] and [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) programs.
  - Despite widening spreads and rising yields,  the manager increases exposure to EUR-USD exchange rates to benefit from carry [returns](../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Asset%20Pricing%20Theory%20Overview/Chapter%203%20-%20%20Assets,%20Portfolios,%20and%20Arbitrage/Assets.md).

#### 2.2.2 Basket Trades

- **Definition**
  - Basket trades involve executing multiple buy and sell orders simultaneously,  often used in systematic or quantitative [investment](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) processes.
- **Applications**
  - Rebalancing portfolios to reflect changing market conditions or model reallocations.
  - Adjusting factor exposures,  [duration](../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Chapter%205/Key%20Rates%20O1s%20Durations%20and%20Hedging.md),  and maturity allocations.
- **Challenges in Basket Trades**
  - [Bid and Ask](Class%20Note%209%20[[Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information) Prices With Private Information|[bid-ask](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Bid-Ask%20Prices%20with%20Adverse%20SelectionPrivate%20Information.md) spreads]],  [portfolio](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) size,  transaction costs,  illiquid securities,  and [market volatility](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%209-%20Bailouts%20and%20Bank%20Failures/Class%20Slides%20On%20Terrausd%20Runs%202.md).

## 3. [bid-ask spreads](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information.md) and Liquidity

### 3.1 Understanding [bid-ask spreads](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information.md)

- **Definition**
  - The [Bid and Ask](Class%20Note%209%20[[Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information) Prices With Private Information|[bid-ask spread](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Bid%20Ask%20and%20Transaction%20Prices%20in%20a%20Specialist%20Market%20With%20Heterogeneously%20Informed%20Traders.md)]] is the difference between the highest price a buyer is willing to pay (bid) and the lowest price a seller is willing to accept (ask).
- **Key Insights**
  - [Bid and Ask](Class%20Note%209%20[[Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information) Prices With Private Information|[bid-ask](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Bid-Ask%20Prices%20with%20Adverse%20SelectionPrivate%20Information.md) spreads]] are indicative of [market liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets/Fixed%20Income%20Securities%20Tools%20for%20Today's%20Markets/Front%20Matter/Trading%20and%20Liquidity.md) but are not definitive measures.
  - Real executed prices often deviate from quoted [Bid and Ask](Class%20Note%209%20[[Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information) Prices With Private Information|[bid-ask](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Bid-Ask%20Prices%20with%20Adverse%20SelectionPrivate%20Information.md) spreads]] due to market demand,  supply,  and trade size.

### 3.2 Determinants of [bid-ask spreads](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information.md)

- **Factors Influencing Spreads**
  - [Portfolio](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) size and transaction costs.
  - Market cycle and volatility.
  - [Demand and supply](../../International%20Finance/China%20Foreign%20Exchange%20Reserves/Currency%20Appreciation%20and%20Depreciation.md) dynamics.
  - Central bank monetary policies (e.g.,  purchase programs).
  - Allocation preferences.
- **Impact of Central Bank Purchases**
  - Central banks' demand for short-term [investment](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md)-grade bonds increases [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) for these securities but reduces [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) for non-[investment](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md)-grade and off-the-run bonds.
- **Relationship with Bond Characteristics**
  - [Bid and Ask](Class%20Note%209%20[[Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information) Prices With Private Information|[bid-ask](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Bid-Ask%20Prices%20with%20Adverse%20SelectionPrivate%20Information.md) spreads]] are positively correlated with bond maturity and inversely correlated with issue size.
  - Larger issues tend to have narrower spreads due to higher [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md).

### 3.3 Challenges in Measuring Liquidity

- **[Bid and Ask](Class%20Note%209%20[[Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information) Prices With Private Information|[bid-ask](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Bid-Ask%20Prices%20with%20Adverse%20SelectionPrivate%20Information.md) spreads]] as Approximate Indicators**
  - [Bid and Ask](Class%20Note%209%20[[Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information) Prices With Private Information|[bid-ask](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Bid-Ask%20Prices%20with%20Adverse%20SelectionPrivate%20Information.md) spreads]] provide a rough measure of [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) but may not reflect actual market conditions.
  - For example,  a bond with a narrow [Bid and Ask](Class%20Note%209%20[[Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information) Prices With Private Information|[bid-ask spread](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Bid%20Ask%20and%20Transaction%20Prices%20in%20a%20Specialist%20Market%20With%20Heterogeneously%20Informed%20Traders.md)]] may still be untradeable due to insufficient demand.
- **Examples of [Liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) Challenges**
  - **Exhibit 44-2:** A bond with a low [bid-ask spread](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Bid%20Ask%20and%20Transaction%20Prices%20in%20a%20Specialist%20Market%20With%20Heterogeneously%20Informed%20Traders.md) ($35 \text{ bps}$) appears liquid but is untradeable due to lack of market participants.
  - **Exhibit 44-3:** A high-yield bond with a quoted [Bid and Ask](Class%20Note%209%20[[Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information) Prices With Private Information|[bid-ask spread](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Bid%20Ask%20and%20Transaction%20Prices%20in%20a%20Specialist%20Market%20With%20Heterogeneously%20Informed%20Traders.md)]] of $0.029$ is rejected by multiple brokers for a $500,     000$ notional trade.

## 4. Practical Examples of [bid-ask spreads](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information.md) and Trades

### 4.1 Intra-Sectoral Relative Value Trades (Exhibit 44-2)

- **Scenario**
  - A bond manager switches between short-term and mid-term bonds within the same sector based on roll-down [returns](../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Asset%20Pricing%20Theory%20Overview/Chapter%203%20-%20%20Assets,%20Portfolios,%20and%20Arbitrage/Assets.md) and option-adjusted spreads (OAS).
- **Key Observations**
  - A short-term bond with a spread of $178 \text{ bps}$ is sold,  and a fundamentally solid bond with a similar roll-down return and OAS of $-10 \text{ bps}$ is purchased.
  - Despite favorable [fundamentals](../../Advanced%20Financial%20Analysis%20and%20Valuation/Lecture%20Notes%20Advanced%20Financial%20Analysis%20and%20Valuation/Week%202/Week%202%20Fundamentals%20Of%20Forecasting.md),  some trades are unexecutable due to insufficient market demand.

### 4.2 High-Yield Bond Trade Illiquidity (Exhibit 44-3)

- **Scenario**
  - A bond manager attempts to sell a high-yield bond with a $500 \text{ million}$ issue size and $3.5$ years to maturity.
- **Key Observations**
  - Multiple brokers reject the trade despite reasonable [Bid and Ask](Class%20Note%209%20[[Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information) Prices With Private Information|[bid-ask](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Bid-Ask%20Prices%20with%20Adverse%20SelectionPrivate%20Information.md) spreads]].
  - The bond can only be sold as part of a basket trade,  highlighting the limitations of single-bond electronic trading.

### 4.3 Emerging Market Debt Instruments (Exhibit 44-4)

- **Key Insights**
  - Emerging market debt typically trades at wider [Bid and Ask](Class%20Note%209%20[[Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information) Prices With Private Information|[bid-ask](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Bid-Ask%20Prices%20with%20Adverse%20SelectionPrivate%20Information.md) spreads]] than developed market bonds.
  - Liquid tenors vary by country,  with shorter maturities generally being more liquid.

### 4.4 Real Bond Portfolio Basket (Exhibit 44-5)

- **Scenario**
  - A $50 \text{ million}$ [portfolio](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) comprising $63$ bonds is traded as a basket.
- **Key Observations**
  - [Bid and Ask](Class%20Note%209%20[[Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information) Prices With Private Information|[bid-ask](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Bid-Ask%20Prices%20with%20Adverse%20SelectionPrivate%20Information.md) spreads]] for sectors like banks,  industrials,  and utilities are much larger when considering real executed prices compared to quoted spreads.
  - [Liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) issues are more pronounced in these sectors,  despite narrow quoted spreads.

## 5. Implications for Portfolio Management

### 5.1 Impact of [bid-ask spreads](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information.md) on Portfolio Turnover

- **Transaction Costs**
  - High [Bid and Ask](Class%20Note%209%20[[Class%20Note%209%20Bid%20and%20Ask%20Prices%20With%20Private%20Information) Prices With Private Information|[bid-ask](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Bid-Ask%20Prices%20with%20Adverse%20SelectionPrivate%20Information.md) spreads]] increase transaction costs,  reducing [portfolio](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md) [returns](../../Financial%20Markets/Financial%20Asset%20Pricing%20Theory%20Overview/Chapter%203%20-%20%20Assets,%20Portfolios,%20and%20Arbitrage/Assets.md).
  - Managers must carefully evaluate trade execution strategies to minimize costs.
- **[Liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) Premium**
  - Illiquid securities often carry a [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) premium,  which can only be realized over long holding periods.
  - This may harm the [portfolio](../../Advanced%20Investments/An%20Asset%20Allocation%20Primer.md)'s risk-return profile if not managed properly.

### 5.2 Strategies to Mitigate Liquidity Challenges

- **Basket Trades**
  - Trading illiquid securities as part of a basket (e.g.,  "Bid Wanted in Competition" or BWIC) can improve execution success.
- **Diversification**
  - Broad diversification across sectors,  maturities,  and currencies reduces reliance on individual illiquid securities.
- **Monitoring Market Conditions**
  - Managers must stay informed about market cycles,  central bank activities,  and demand-supply dynamics to anticipate [liquidity](../../Financial%20Markets%20and%20Institutions/III.%20Liquidity%20of%20Assets/Class%205-%20Private%20Information,%20Liquidity,%20and%20Securitization/Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Class%20Note%2010%20Liquidity%20and%20Liquidity%20Managementliquidity%20management.md) shifts.

